The new research could explain why women are more likely to get brain tumours than men.

It also appears that meningiomas have become more common over the past few years, which could be due to the increasing popularity of HRT.

Hormones such as oestrogen are prescribed to middle-aged women to alleviate symptoms of the menopause such as hot flushes and joint pain.

However, HRT has previously been linked to an increased risk of serious conditions such as cancer, heart attacks and strokes.

Cancer Research UK recommends that women use HRT for as short a time as possible to minimise the possibility of adverse side effects.

